Mid-Term Project¶

Overview¶

  • Use Medicare CCLF Claims from Syntegra dataset to answer key business questions
  • Extra credit for building up on the questions below (additional questions + answers)
  • One Jupyter notebook solution with clear Python code and all cell outputs available
  • At least two data quality checks

Step 0. Prepare raw input datasets¶

Here we will 1) load original datasets, 2) remove unused columns, 3) de-duplicate rows, and 4) join datasets, not necessarily in this order

Assumptions:

  • Claim ID (cur_clm_uniq_id) represents one claim, which may or may not have more than one code (code could be HCPCS/CPT, diagnosis, procedure...)
  • There is a one-to-many relationship between patient IDs (bene_mbi_id) and claim IDs (cur_clm_uniq_id), i.e. each claim is unique to one patient, but one patient can have more than one claim

Business insights Q.1 CVM claims :¶

  • Portfolio Stability: The CVM sector's consistent 12-13% market share over the years underscores its role as a stable revenue generator. For sales and marketing leadership, this isn't just a "safe" sector; it's the financial bedrock.

  • Resource Arbitrage: Given the stable but non-explosive growth in CVM claims this sector can be considered "resource bank" In times when we need to push resources to high-growth but riskier sectors, we know we can afford to pull back here without catastrophic consequences.

  • Messaging Sophistication: The communication with HCPs shouldn't just be about the efficacy of CVM products. It should be about "partnership over patronage." The message should convey that we're not just a vendor but a strategic partner committed to long-term healthcare outcomes.

Resource- https://www.bcg.com/publications/2018/how-to-make-pharma-manufacturing-partnerships-more-strategic

Strategic Next Steps:¶

  • High-Margin Focus: Drilling down into the top 100 HCPCS/CPT codes to identify those that are not just popular but also high-margin. These are the "killer apps" in the CVM space.

  • Competitive War Room: Setting up a task force to conduct SWAT-style competitive analysis. Identifying not just where we're losing but also where competitors are weak for market share capture.

  • ROI Mapping: Every dollar spent on the CVM sector should be tracked for ROI. If certain tactics or channels are underperforming, the funds should be reallocated swiftly to high-ROI activities.

  • Geo-Strategic Campaigns: Using data analytics that can pinpoint regions with a higher propensity for CVM claims, those are your "gold mines" (as professor likes to call it). Allocating disproportionate resources there and build localized campaigns.

  • Demographic Deep Dive: Are younger patients more prone to CVM claims? Or is it the older demographic? Knowing this can help in tailoring not just the product but also the messaging, pricing, and even the sales channels to target.

By adopting these insights and strategies, the sales and marketing leadership can not only defend but potentially expand the market share in the CVM sector, optimizing both top-line and bottom-line performance.

Business Insights Q.2. a) iv. Analysis of HCP Behavior in Context of Claim Volume from 2016-2018 for CVM¶

Observations:¶

Observations:

  • The number of HCPs in the Segment #1: Disease Aware segment is increasing each year.
  • The Segment #2: Trialists segment is also showing a moderate increase.
  • The Segment #3: Rising Stars segment is relatively stable, with a slight decrease in 2018.
  • The Segment #4: High-Volume Prescribers segment is fluctuating but showed an increase in 2018.

Implications for Sales Force Deployment¶

Segmentation of HCPs:

  • Disease Aware (1 CVM claim): These HCPs are likely to be less familiar with the product.
  • Trialists (2-4 CVM claims): These HCPs have some level of engagement.
  • Rising Stars (5-9 CVM claims): These are well-engaged HCPs but are fewer in number.
  • High-Volume Prescribers (10+ CVM claims): These are the key opinion leaders in the field.

Allocation Strategy:¶

Allocation Strategy:

  • Segment #1 Disease Aware: Non-Personal Promotions (NPP) like emails and social media campaigns to increase awareness.
  • Segment #2 Trialists: A mix of In-Person and NPP.
  • Segment #3 Rising Stars: Primarily In-Person visits to deepen the relationship and provide tailored solutions.
  • Segment #4 High-Volume Prescribers: In-Person visits are crucial. These HCPs can also be involved in webinars or as speakers in seminars.

Business Insights Q.2. a) v. How would you determine which sales tactic is best for which segment?¶

Determining Best Sales Tactic for Each Segment:¶

  • Disease Aware: A/B testing of different NPP methods to see which is most effective in driving engagement.
  • Trialists: Use analytics to track the effectiveness of in-person visits versus NPP.
  • Rising Stars: Customer Relationship Management (CRM) data can be analyzed to understand the needs and preferences of these HCPs.
  • High-Volume Prescribers:ROI analysis of in-person visits and other high-engagement activities.

Resource : https://www.pharmavoice.com/news/non-personal-promotion/613321/

Business Insights for Gender-Based Trends & Strategic Recommendations¶

Female (F) Gender Group:¶

  • Trend: The claim count for females has been consistently increasing from 2128 in 2016 to 2774 in 2018. The Year-over-Year (YoY) change was 14.76% between 2016 and 2017, and 13.60% between 2017 and 2018.
  • Strategic Recommendations: Given the consistent and moderate increase in claims, it would be prudent to allocate a substantial budget for preventive healthcare programs specifically targeting women. Programs could include women's health screenings and educational campaigns on lifestyle diseases that are prevalent among females.

Male (M) Gender Group:¶

  • Trend: The claim count for males increased from 1434 in 2016 to 2049 in 2018. The YoY change was 11.44% between 2016 and 2017, but there was a significant spike of 28.22% between 2017 and 2018.
  • Strategic Recommendations: The sharp YoY increase between 2017 and 2018 indicates a growing demand for medical services among males. It would be advisable to allocate a larger portion of the budget for this demographic, focusing on specialized care packages. Given the significant YoY increase, early detection and preventive care programs should be a priority to manage future claim volumes effectively.
